      <div xml:id="NA172-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu pakaṟkuṟi vanta talaimakaṉait tōḻi varaivu kaṭāyatu.
            2. kuṟip peyarttiṭumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is how the confidante urged HIM for marriage who had come to the day tryst. 2. It is also how he came back from the tryst.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA172">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            viḷaiyā ṭāyamoṭu veṇmaṇa laḻutti</l>
<l>            maṟantaṉan tuṟanta kāḻmuḷai yakaiya</l>
<l>            neypey tīmpāl peytaṉam vaḷarppa</l>
<l>            nummiṉuñ ciṟantatu nuvvai yākumeṉ</l>
<l>            ṟaṉṉai kūṟiṉaḷ puṉṉaiyatu ciṟappē </l>
<l>            yamma nāṇutu nummoṭu nakaiyē</l>
<l>            viruntiṟ pāṇar viḷaricai kaṭuppa</l>
<l>            valampuri vāṉkōṭu naralu milaṅkunīrt</l>
<l>            tuṟaikeḻu koṇkanī nalki</l>
<l>            ṉiṟaipaṭu nīḻal piṟavumā ruḷavē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Mother talked of the distinctiveness of [this] Puṉṉai tree:</l>
<l rend="indent2">“this, being more special than you, is [your] younger sister”,</l>
<l rend="indent">when a sprout came out from the core abandoned and forgotten by us<note place="foot">With <term xml:lang="ta">maṟantaṉam</term> and with <term xml:lang="ta">peytaṉam</term> (next line) we are once more faced with the finite forms used as participial noun, the <term xml:lang="ta">muṟṟeccam</term>. Else we can consider splitting up the sentences: "Pressing [it] into the white sand together with [our] playmates, we forgot [it]. When a sprout came out of the abandoned core, we poured sweet milk mixed with ghee [on it]. When we had made it grow, mother talked...".</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">pressed into the white sand, together with [our] playmates,</l>
<l rend="indent">[and] when we made it grow by pouring sweet milk mixed with ghee</l>
<l rend="indent4">[on it].</l>
<l>Alas, we would be ashamed of smiling<note place="foot">Here <term xml:lang="ta">nakai</term> "smile" undeniably has erotic connotations of quite a strong nature, which might be a reason to reconsider its use in general.</note> with you [by its side].</l>
<l rend="indent3">If you allow it, man from the coast of ghats</l>
<l rend="indent2">with shining water, where the right-spiralled white conches are sounding</l>
<l rend="indent3">as the sounding music of the bards in a feast,</l>
<l>– there are also other [trees] with a full shade.</l>
        </lg>
